<B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=5><P ALIGN="CENTER">Functions Learning Plan 2</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER">Linear Functions</P>
</FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=4><P ALIGN="CENTER"></P>
</B></FONT><FONT FACE="Arial"><P>While working through this plan you should be referring to your lecture notes titled ‘Functions’.</P>

<B><P>Linear Functions</P>

</B><P>A linear function has the general form:</P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER">y = f(x) = mx + c</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER">where m and c are constants</P>

<B><P>Note</P>
</B><P>In a linear function the power of the unknown variable (here x) will be 1.   The graph of a linear function will be a straight line, where m is the gradient of the line and c is the point at which the line cuts the y-axis.</P>

<P>Families of linear functions:</P>

<P>f(x) = mx ; (c =0) are straight lines which pass through the origin with gradient m.</P>

<P>f(x) = x + c; (m = 1) are straight lines which pass through (0,c) with gradient 1.   These lines will be parallel as they have equal gradients.</P>

<P>f(x) = c is a horizontal line where y takes the value c no matter the value of x.</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>
<B><P>Example</P>
</B>
<P>A product sells at £400 per unit.   The revenue function is a linear function,</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER">R(x) = 400x &#9;where x is the number of units sold.</P>
<P>Setting up a table of values.</P>
